This week we are setting time aside to reflect. It has been one full year since COVID-19 became a global pandemic and caused widespread lockdowns. The impact of crises is never gender neutral, and COVID-19 is no exception. While everyone has been facing unprecedented challenges, women — especially mothers — have unique struggles. Meet Tribin, a mother of four in Bangladesh, and discover why the pandemic and all its challenges have made her believe in miracles.

#compassioninternational #covid_19 #womenshistorymonth

“I really believe that everybody has gifts and talents but for me, everything took me back to beauty and style. I believe that the project and the church gave me a place to take advantage of that talent and gift.”

“I do believe that God called me to do this and gives me the passion for it. I see myself in at least 5 years with my own house, my own business and being my own boss. I feel really proud when my son sees me as a hard working mama, as a super mama.” 

Sandy, Colombia 

#WomensHistoryMonth #CompassionAlumni

node.text: Meet Racquel, a 19-year-old in the Philippines who has always dreamed of becoming a doctor — regardless of the intense poverty surrounding her. node.text:
Sponsorship means so much more than just a donation ... it means hope! 💛

When 6-year-old Fortune received the first letter from her sponsor, it brought her entire family joy — which can be hard to find when facing the challenges of poverty.

"That night, I could see the happiness of my wife. She rarely gets happy about things," says Tsokewo, Fortune's father. "But after we received the letter, she was so joyful."

Fortune loves her sponsor's letters, and they are very precious to her. Her father helps her keep them in a safe place in their room. From time to time, Fortune takes out the letters and goes through them to relive the love for her sponsor.

"I want to thank my sponsor for having not forgotten me. I love her and her letters." — Fortune

Meet Keshia, a rising star gymnast in a small town in Indonesia. ✨

This 11-year-old has been doing gymnastics for three years now. Even though she is relatively new to the sport, she has been showing promising talent. 

Keshia started going to a Compassion center at age 3 and has been consistently encouraged to explore her interests. Her family wants to support her dreams, but it's difficult to cover all expenses when her father makes $100 a month. It is because of her involvement in Compassion's program that she is able to pursue her dreams!

Nine-year-old Judith, her 1-year-old sister and the rest of their family were evicted from their rented room and lost most of their belongings. They moved into a new place but had no furniture, cooking supplies or beds.
 
They're not alone. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, many families are at risk of losing their homes. Families in poverty are at an even higher risk.

But through Compassion's Highly Vulnerable Children's Care fund, Judith's family received a bed, closet, oven, clothes — and hope for tomorrow!
 
"I can't believe it! We are not going to sleep on the floor anymore, and my mom won't have to walk looking for places to cook." — Judith

Brisaida is a warrior with a heart of hope. 💛

The 3-year-old miraculously survived a fall from a second story window. But her injuries required hospital visits and a medical test her parents couldn’t afford. Brisaida’s father, Cesar, makes only about $6 a day as a moto-taxi driver. 

But God continued to send help for Brisaida and her family: Compassion covered the cost of a CT scan, which revealed that Brisaida’s injuries were so minor they would heal on their own. Now she’s back to her energetic, curious self. 

It is because of your generous giving that this family experienced a miraculous recovery and never lost hope!
 
#WarriorWednesday

A split decision saved Ivis’ family from disaster. In November 2020, Ivis decided that her family would abandon their home in the middle of the night to seek refuge from torrential rains. 
 
“We never experienced a mudslide before. It just invaded our home and swept away everything we owned,” says Ivis. “I was heartbroken to see our house partially destroyed. We had nowhere to go — not even a bed to sleep in. Piles and piles of polluted mud ruined the few belongings we had.” 
 
Thanks to the Highly Vulnerable Children (HVC) fund, emergency aid was given to the family to help rebuild their home. Now baby Alessandro has a safe, new home to grow up in. 💙

In Kenya, every child has the right to basic education. The country has witnessed significant literacy gains in recent years, but crowded classrooms can still affect learning. 

In some areas, the pupil-to-teacher ratio is as high as 77 to 1. 

As part of Compassion’s program, children receive educational support. They have access to tutoring at child development centers, and their sponsors help pay for school fees, uniforms and supplies!

node.text:
Water is something we tend to take for granted.

But 1 in 3 people do not have access to clean water globally. June Rey is no longer one of those people! With the help of Compassion’s church partner, June Rey and his family now have access to safe water. Water filters have helped eliminate the threat of waterborne health issues they suffered in the past.

The smile on June Rey’s face says more than words ever could. 😊💧💙

node.text:
Gunmen assassinated Haitian President Jovenel Moïse and wounded his wife on Wednesday in a raid on their home. This has happened at a time when Haiti is experiencing economic, political and social distress.

As a precautionary measure, Compassion Haiti offices have been temporarily closed, but all our Haitian staff are safe. The Haitian government has declared a state of siege, which might lead to temporary interruptions to Compassion’s programs. Compassion will continue to deliver relief supplies and check on families as allowed.

Please pray with us for wisdom for the leaders of Haiti; peace for children and their families who are dealing with fear about the future of their country; the recovery of the First Lady and her family; and Compassion staff and volunteers as they minister to children in this difficult and frightening time.

#PrayForHaiti
